[1539.24127, "o", "\u001b[33;13H\u001b[30m\u001b[103md\u001b[34;2H\u001b[m\u000fextension=g\u001b[35;2Hextension=g\u001b[67;14H\u001b[?25h"]
[1540.959837, "o", "\u001b[?25l\r\u001b[67;1H\u001b[13X\u001b[H\u001b[0;10;4;1m\u000f\u001b[96m[\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[96mPHP\u001b[0;10;4;1m\u000f\u001b[96m]\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[17X\r\n\u001b[22X\u001b[3;20H   \r\n; About php.ini   ;\u001b[5;2H;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;\u001b[55X\u001b[6;3HPHP's initialization file, generally called php.ini, is responsible for\u001b[7;2H configuring many of the aspects of PHP's behavior.\r\n\u001b[24X\u001b[9;2H PHP attempts to find and load this configuration from a number of locations.\u001b[10;3HThe following is a summary of its search order:\u001b[11;2H 1. SAPI module specific location.\u001b[12;3H2. The PHPRC environment variable.\u001b[13;2H 3. A number of predefined registry keys on Windows\u001b[14;3H4. Current working directory (except CLI)\u001b[33X\u001b[15;3H5. The web server's directory (for SAPI modules), or directory of PHP\u001b[16;2H (otherwise in Windows)\u001b[17;3H6. The directory from the --with-config-file-path compile time option, or the\u001b[18;2H Windows directory (usually C:\\windows)\u001b[19;3HSee the PHP docs for more specific information.\u001b[26X\u001b[20;3Hhttps://php.net/configuration.file\u001b[36X\r\n\u001b[75X\u001b[22;3HThe syntax of the file is extremely simple.  Whitespace and lines\u001b[23;2H beginning with a semicolon are silently ignored (as you probably guessed).\u001b[24;2H Section headers (e.g. [Foo]) are also silently ignored, even though\u001b[25;2H they might mean something in the future.\r\n\u001b[19X\n; Directives following the section heading [PATH=/www/mysite] only\u001b[28;2H apply to PHP files in the /www/mysite directory.  Directives\u001b[29;2H following the section heading [HOST=www.example.com] only apply to\u001b[30;2H PHP files served from www.example.com.  Directives set in these\u001b[31;2H special sections cannot be overridden by user-defined INI files or\u001b[32;2H at runtime. Currently, [PATH=] and [HOST=] sections only work under\u001b[33;2H CGI/FastCGI.\u001b[34;2H https://php.net/ini.sections\r\n\u001b[14X\u001b[36;2H Directives are specified using the following syntax:\u001b[37;2H directive = value\u001b[38;2H Directive names are *case sensitive* - foo=bar is different from FOO=bar.\u001b[39;2H Directives are variables used to configure PHP or PHP extensions.\u001b[40;2H There is no name validation.  If PHP can't find an expected\u001b[41;2H directive because it is not set or is mistyped, a default value will be used.\r\n\u001b[20X\u001b[43;2H The value can be a string, a number, a PHP constant (e.g. E_ALL or M_PI), one\u001b[44;2H of the INI constants (On, Off, True, False, Yes, No and None) or an expression\u001b[45;2H (e.g. E_ALL & ~E_NOTICE), a quoted string (\"bar\"), or a reference to a\u001b[46;2H previously set variable or directive (e.g. ${foo})\r\n\u001b[16X\u001b[48;2H Expressions in the INI file are limited to bitwise operators and parentheses:\u001b[49;2H |  bitwise OR\u001b[50;2H ^  bitwise XOR  \u001b[51;2H &  bitwise AND \u001b[52;2H ~  bitwise NOT  \u001b[53;2H !  boolean NOT  \r\n\u001b[18X\u001b[55;2H Boolean flags can be turned on using the values 1, On, True or Yes.\u001b[56;2H They can be turned off using the values 0, Off, False or No.\r\n\u001b[14X\n; An empty string can be denoted by simply not writing anything after the equal\r\n; sign, or by using the None keyword:\r\n\u001b[19X\u001b[61;3Hfoo =         ; sets foo to an empty string\u001b[62;2H foo = None    ; sets foo to an empty string\r\n; foo = \"None\"  ; sets foo to the string 'None'\r\n\u001b[12X\u001b[65;3HIf you use constants in your value, and these constants belong to a\u001b[6X\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f1,1            Top\u001b[?112c\u001b[?1002h\u001b[?1006h\u001b[H\u001b[?25h"]
